data.content:
Here's what happened and how to fix it:

**The problem:** C# 14 introduces new implicit span conversions. When the compiler sees `array.Contains(num)` on an `int[]`, it now resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Span-based methods **cannot be represented in expression trees**, so this throws at runtime (typically an `InvalidOperationException` or `NotSupportedException`).

**Fix options — cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` to force the LINQ binding:**

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Any of these forces the compiler to pick `Enumerable.Contains`, which is expression-tree-compatible. The same pattern applies to `.Reverse()` on arrays — use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` or `.AsEnumerable().Reverse()`.
